text: hi everyone anthony fantano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of this new injury
reserve project by the time i get to
phoenix this is the latest project from
phoenix hip-hop outfit injury reserve
their second studio lp to date following
up their self-titled in 2019 which was
officially their debut though it did
come after years of fan favorite
mixtapes and the drive it like it's
stolen ep i've been following injury
reserves rise since the release of early
singles that preceded their live from
the dentist's breakout mixtape and it's
been exciting to see them progress
artistically but also disheartening to
see their fun and forward-thinking
approach to rap music fall on deaf ears
within much of the industry that self
title definitely did make a dent forcing
many outlets to really pay attention to
them with some more accessible tracks
and bigger features though personally i
don't think it lived up to be their best
work to date now under normal conditions
any other group most likely would have
built off the rapport and momentum
set by that record with a new release
but the pandemic year a darker world and
the untimely passing of key member
jordan alexander groggs has put injury
reserve in an unforeseen position where
the you know future of the group is
pretty much up in the air right now but
in an interview i had with remaining
members nathaniel richie and parker
corey they said they finished much of
the lp before all of this and because of
its dark and abstract direction it still
felt fitting to put out and that's
certainly what the singles teased toward
as well there was the heart-wrenching
knees which brought these stark hits of
guitars and drums over which richie
brings this pained and ghostly vocal
delivery that blurs the lines between
the performance style of a rapper and r
b artist and a rock frontman the track
even blurs the boundaries of what is i
guess a song as there are moments here
where richie's lyrics and vocals feel
less like a performance and more like an
internal monologue wrapped in off-kilter
rhythms glitchy effects and disorienting
vocal samples as a whole though the song
feels like singing a
very quiet song to yourself at a point
where where you are at your lowest while
also dealing with a pounding headache
then there was also superman that which
was even more disorienting in comparison
with its wild frantic glitchy rhythms
that are still baffling to me at this
point in one breath i feel like i'm
listening to a more direct and pummeling
version of something off of an arca
record one of her more i guess uh
deconstructed and glitch-oriented
projects while richie's vocals in the
midst of this chaos are giving off this
ranting raving auto-tuned 808s and
heartbreak
kanye level energy the ending of the
track is a little abrupt but the ride up
until that point is completely dizzying
overwhelming too but in the midst of all
this injury reserve still manages to
convey some very potent emotions like
the song knees this track brings i think
some really serious feelings of
helplessness or even impending doom so
with teaser tracks with singles like
these i went into this album wondering
is every track gonna be this like left
field and by the time i get to phoenix
is almost more out there than i
anticipated it would be to the point
where i find some pockets of the record
groundbreaking and a little difficult to
define so there's outside the intro
track which is a pretty mysterious
beginning to the record and feels like
i'm listening to
a dystopian rap battle spoken word piece
the stage is set with some sampled bars
from new york battle rapper dot then
immediately after richie comes in
rapping against that with his vocals
pitched down almost as if he is
performing in response but not literally
it's not like he's going at the guy or
anything like that i think this is sort
of setting the stage on this track in
order to illustrate these themes of
division expressed throughout the song
it's a really immense intro to the
record and i think speaks to the
direness of our current times and i
think speaks to the emotional heaviness
of this record overall as well as it
very much feels like i'm staring into
a black hole that i'm slowly getting
sucked into ss san francisco with z
loopers is also a serious head scratcher
the instrumental on this one sounds like
i'm listening to some depressive
rockabilly or maybe even some tom waits
from like the bone machine era with its
twangy and strange guitar leads and
brooding bass meanwhile the vocals
richie and z loopers throw on top are

following rap verses that pop in are the
epitome of abstract hip-hop with
allusions
to just how dark the world is right now

being constantly interrupted with other

know just things trailing off a little
bit mentally the song itself trails off
a little bit in the end but as i listen
to it and also enjoy it i do kind of
wonder what is even the most reasonable
way to end this because as i dig deeper
into this record not only does it feel
like a lot of it is in reaction to the
disarray of the world but also the
disarray of the self the song footwork

with these dreary lo-fi guitar and drum

especially with that
guitar loop and drum loop stalin out a

willingness to continue and a
hopefulness to
uh the vibe here that i think is

uh i walked away from this record really
blown away and impressed this thing is a

first records in hip hop since
the release of like death grips early

explored a bit deeper in terms of like

there are moments when phoenix i think

very minor shortcomings this record is
the experimental out there abstract
hip-hop release that i think everybody
should be listening to this year if that
is a direction that you happen to find
yourself going into at any point because
this is just great in my opinion it
totally blows their self-titled project

feels so familiar but also so different
